ction{Cybersecurity Risk\nManagement}\\label{cybersecurity-risk-management}\n\n\\subsection{1. Learning Objectives}\\label{learning-objectives}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  Define and differentiate between key cybersecurity risk management\n  frameworks.\n\\item\n  Identify and assess potential threats and vulnerabilities within an\n  organization’s environment.\n\\item\n  Develop a prioritized risk mitigation strategy based on established\n  methodologies.\n\\item\n  Understand the role of compliance and regulatory standards in\n  cybersecurity risk management.\n\\item\n  Articulate the importance of continuous monitoring and adaptation\n  within a cybersecurity risk management program.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{2. Executive Overview}\\label{executive-overview}\n\nCybersecurity risk management is a globally pervasive imperative. The\nincreasing interconnectedness of systems – from critical infrastructure\nto personal devices – has created a vast attack surface for malicious\nactors. The cost of cybercrime is estimated to reach trillions of\ndollars annually, impacting businesses of all sizes, governments, and\nindividuals. Organizations across every industry – finance, healthcare,\nmanufacturing, retail – are targeted due to the value of data,\nintellectual property, operational control, and disruption potential.\nEffective risk management is no longer simply a technical exercise; it’s\na strategic business imperative that protects assets, maintains\noperational continuity, and safeguards reputation. The field draws on\nprinciples from operations management, financial analysis, and legal\ncompliance to provide a holistic approach to security. Furthermore, it’s\ntightly interwoven with evolving regulations like GDPR, CCPA, HIPAA, and\nsector-specific standards driven by bodies like NIST, ISO, and\nindustry-specific frameworks.\n\n\\subsection{3. Core Concepts \\& Technical\nDefinitions}\\label{core-concepts-technical-definitions}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Management:} The systematic process of identifying,\n  assessing, and controlling risks. It’s not about eliminating risk\n  entirely – which is often impractical – but about understanding and\n  accepting the residual risk remaining after mitigation efforts.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Threat:} A potential cause of harm to an asset. Threats can be\n  malicious (e.g., hackers, malware) or unintentional (e.g., human\n  error, system failure).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Vulnerability:} A weakness in a system or process that can be\n  exploited by a threat. Vulnerabilities can be technical (e.g.,\n  unpatched software) or procedural (e.g., weak passwords).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk:} The combined effect of a threat exploiting a\n  vulnerability. Quantitatively, risk is often expressed as the\n  probability of a threat occurring multiplied by the impact if it does.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Residual Risk:} The level of risk that remains after\n  implementing mitigation controls. It’s crucial to acknowledge and\n  manage residual risk, as complete elimination is frequently\n  unattainable.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Appetite:} The level of risk an organization is willing\n  to accept in pursuit of its objectives. This is a critical factor in\n  determining the appropriate level of investment in risk mitigation\n  controls.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{4. In-Depth Subject Matter\nCoverage}\\label{in-depth-subject-matter-coverage}\n\n\\subsubsection{4.1 Risk Management\nFrameworks}\\label{risk-management-frameworks}\n\nRisk management frameworks provide structured methodologies for\nassessing and managing cybersecurity risks. Several widely adopted\nframeworks exist, each with strengths and weaknesses.\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF):} Developed by the National\n  Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the CSF is a voluntary\n  framework that provides a scalable, adaptable approach to managing\n  cybersecurity risk. It’s organized around five core functions:\n  Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, and Recover. The CSF relies on\n  risk management practices consistent with industry standards and\n  guidelines. \\textbf{Best Practice:} Organizations often use the CSF as\n  a foundational framework, tailoring it to their specific needs and\n  risk profile.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{ISO 27001:} An internationally recognized standard for\n  Information Security Management Systems (ISMS). It provides a\n  comprehensive set of controls and processes for managing information\n  security risks, from initial assessment through ongoing monitoring and\n  improvement. \\textbf{Common Pitfall:} Implementing ISO 27001 solely as\n  a compliance exercise without embedding it into an organization’s\n  culture is ineffective.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{COBIT:} A framework developed by ISACA (Information Systems\n  Audit and Control Association) that focuses on the governance and\n  management of IT. While broader than just cybersecurity, COBIT offers\n  significant benefits in aligning IT with business objectives and\n  managing cybersecurity risks within the IT landscape.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\begin{quote}\n\\emph{Example: A small e-commerce business might find the NIST CSF\nsufficient for initial risk assessment and mitigation, while a large\nfinancial institution would likely require a comprehensive\nimplementation of ISO 27001 coupled with COBIT for robust governance.}\n\\end{quote}\n\n\\subsubsection{4.2 Threat and Vulnerability\nAssessment}\\label{threat-and-vulnerability-assessment}\n\nThis phase involves identifying potential threats and vulnerabilities\nwithin an organization’s systems and processes.\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Threat Modeling:} A proactive approach to identifying\n  potential threats by analyzing an organization’s assets,\n  vulnerabilities, and potential attack vectors. Techniques include\n  STRIDE (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure,\n  Denial of Service, Elevation of Privilege) and attack trees.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Vulnerability Scanning:} Automated tools that scan systems and\n  networks for known vulnerabilities. These scans identify weaknesses\n  that could be exploited by attackers.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Penetration Testing:} Simulated attacks conducted by security\n  professionals to identify vulnerabilities and assess the effectiveness\n  of security controls. These tests are typically more sophisticated\n  than vulnerability scans and involve exploiting vulnerabilities to\n  gain unauthorized access.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Dark Web Monitoring:} Proactively monitoring dark web forums\n  and marketplaces for mentions of the organization’s assets, sensitive\n  data, or vulnerabilities.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\begin{quote}\n\\emph{Industry Standard: Vulnerability scanning and penetration testing\nare often conducted according to established methodologies outlined in\nframeworks like OWASP (Open Web Application Security Project).}\n\\end{quote}\n\n\\subsubsection{4.3 Risk Assessment \\&\nPrioritization}\\label{risk-assessment-prioritization}\n\nOnce threats and vulnerabilities have been identified, risks must be\nassessed and prioritized.\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Qualitative Risk Assessment:} Uses subjective judgments to\n  assess the likelihood and impact of risks. Often uses scales (e.g.,\n  Low, Medium, High) to categorize risks.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Quantitative Risk Assessment:} Uses numerical data to assess\n  risks. This involves calculating the expected monetary loss (EML)\n  associated with a risk.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Prioritization:} Ranking risks based on their potential\n  impact and likelihood. High-priority risks require immediate attention\n  and mitigation. \\textbf{Best Practice:} Utilize a risk matrix\n  (likelihood vs.~impact) to visually represent and prioritize risks.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\begin{quote}\n\\emph{Example: A vulnerability allowing unauthorized access to customer\ndata would likely be rated as “High” risk due to its potential impact on\nprivacy and legal compliance.}\n\\end{quote}\n\n\\subsubsection{4.4 Risk Mitigation \\&\nResponse}\\label{risk-mitigation-response}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Avoidance:} Eliminating the risk altogether by\n  discontinuing the activity that creates the risk.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Transfer:} Shifting the risk to another party, typically\n  through insurance.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Reduction:} Implementing controls to reduce the\n  likelihood or impact of the risk. This is the most common approach.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Risk Acceptance:} Acknowledging the risk and accepting the\n  potential consequences. This is often done for low-impact,\n  low-likelihood risks.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\begin{quote}\n\\emph{Example: An organization might transfer the risk of data breaches\nto an insurance provider, or implement multi-factor authentication to\nreduce the likelihood of unauthorized access.}\n\\end{quote}\n\n\\subsection{5. Summary \\& Actionable\nTakeaways}\\label{summary-actionable-takeaways}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  Cybersecurity risk management is a continuous process, not a one-time\n  event.\n\\item\n  Understanding your organization’s risk appetite is crucial for\n  developing an effective risk management program.\n\\item\n  Utilize established risk management frameworks as a foundation for\n  your efforts.\n\\item\n  Regularly assess and update your risk assessments to reflect changes\n  in the threat landscape and your organization’s environment.\n\\item\n  Prioritize risks based on their potential impact and likelihood.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{6. Glossary of Terms}\\label{glossary-of-terms}\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} Cloud Computing: A model for delivering computing\n  services – including software, storage, and processing power – over\n  the internet (“the cloud”). It offers scalability, flexibility, and\n  cost-effectiveness compared to traditional on-premise infrastructure.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} Cybersecurity: The practice of protecting computer\n  systems and networks from threats such as theft, damage, or\n  disruption. It encompasses a wide range of technologies and practices,\n  including firewalls, intrusion detection systems, and data encryption.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} Vulnerability: A weakness or flaw in a system,\n  software, or process that could be exploited by a threat actor. Common\n  vulnerabilities include software bugs, misconfigurations, and weak\n  passwords.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} Threat: Any potential source of harm to a system,\n  network, or organization. Threats can be malicious (e.g., hackers,\n  malware) or unintentional (e.g., human error, natural disasters).\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} Risk Appetite: The level of risk an organization\n  is willing to accept in pursuit of its objectives. It’s a key factor\n  in determining the type and level of security controls to implement.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} NIST Cybersecurity Framework: A voluntary\n  framework developed by the National Institute of Standards and\n  Technology (NIST) to help organizations manage cybersecurity risk.\n\\item\n  \\textbf{Term Name:} ISO 27001: An international standard for\n  Information Security Management Systems (ISMS), providing a framework\n  for organizations to manage their information security risks.\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsection{7. Knowledge Assessment (Bloom’s Taxonomy\nBased)}\\label{knowledge-assessment-blooms-taxonomy-based}\n\n\\subsubsection{Part A: Recall \\& Comprehension (10\nMCQs)}\\label{part-a-recall-comprehension-10-mcqs}\n\n\\textbf{Q1:} Which of the following best describes a “threat” in the\ncontext of cybersecurity risk management?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A weakness in a system.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A potential cause of harm.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The impact of a successful attack.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    A security control.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q2:} What is the primary purpose of the NIST Cybersecurity\nFramework?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To enforce cybersecurity regulations.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To provide a voluntary framework for managing cybersecurity risk.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To replace all existing cybersecurity standards.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    To solely focus on technical security controls.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q3:} What does “residual risk” represent?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The total risk before any controls are implemented.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The risk remaining after implementing mitigation controls.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The highest possible level of risk.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The risk that is completely eliminated.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q4:} Which of the following is a key component of a Risk\nManagement Framework?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Denial of Service Attacks\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Threat Modeling\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Firewall Configuration\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Network Topology\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q5:} What is a vulnerability scan primarily used for?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Assessing an organization’s overall security posture.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Identifying known weaknesses in systems and networks.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Performing simulated attacks.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Monitoring dark web activity.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q6:} What is a risk appetite?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The amount of money an organization spends on security.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The level of risk an organization is willing to accept.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The number of security incidents an organization experiences.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The effectiveness of an organization’s security controls.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q7:} What does ISO 27001 certify?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The use of specific security technologies.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    An organization’s compliance with a recognized security standard.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The skills of an organization’s security team.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    The level of protection provided by a firewall.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q8:} Which of the following is an example of risk reduction?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Purchasing cybersecurity insurance.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Implementing multi-factor authentication.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Ignoring a known vulnerability.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Accepting a high level of risk.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q9:} What is a “dark web monitor” primarily used for?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Blocking all external network traffic.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Detecting and responding to cybersecurity incidents.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Identifying mentions of an organization’s assets on underground\n    forums and marketplaces.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Auditing an organization’s security policies.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q10:} Which of the following is a characteristic of a ‘High’\nrisk rating?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Low likelihood and low impact.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    High likelihood and low impact.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Low likelihood and high impact.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    High likelihood and high impact.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\textbf{Q11:} A retail company stores customer credit card information\nin a database. Which of the following is the MOST critical risk\nmanagement action they should take?\n\n\\begin{itemize}\n\\tightlist\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Implement a firewall to prevent unauthorized network access.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{1}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Encrypt all sensitive data at rest and in transit.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{2}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Regularly perform vulnerability scans of the database.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\item\n  \\begin{enumerate}\n  \\def\\labelenumi{\\Alph{enumi})}\n  \\setcounter{enumi}{3}\n  \\tightlist\n  \\item\n    Train all employees on cybersecurity best practices.\n  \\end{enumerate}\n\\end{itemize}\n\n\\subsubsection{Part B: Application \\& Analysis (5 Short Answer\nQuestions)}\\label{part-b-application-analysis-5-short-answer-questions}\n\n\\textbf{Q11:} Scenario: “TechCorp” is developing a new mobile app.\nDescribe the first three steps TechCorp should take to assess the\ncybersecurity risks associated with this app. (Answer: Identification of\nassets – the app itself, user data, and associated systems; Threat\nmodeling – identifying potential attackers and their motives;\nVulnerability assessment – scanning the app’s code and infrastructure\nfor weaknesses.)\n\n\\textbf{Q12:} Explain why it’s crucial for an organization to establish\na clear “risk appetite” before implementing any cybersecurity controls.\n(Answer: The risk appetite defines the boundaries of acceptable risk,\nguiding decisions about which risks to address and how much resources to\ninvest in mitigation. Without a defined risk appetite, security efforts\ncould be misaligned with business objectives or overly restrictive.)\n\n\\textbf{Q13:} A manufacturing company discovers a vulnerability in its\nindustrial control system (ICS). Outline the steps the company should\ntake to address this vulnerability, considering both immediate and\nlong-term actions. (Answer: Immediate – Patching the vulnerability,\nisolating the affected system; Long-term – Implementing robust security\nmonitoring, conducting regular vulnerability assessments, incident\nresponse plan.)\n\n\\textbf{Q14:} An organization wants to improve its cybersecurity posture\nbut has limited resources. Rank the following activities in terms of\npriority (High, Medium, Low): 1. Conducting a full penetration test. 2.\nImplementing multi-factor authentication for all critical systems. 3.\nProviding cybersecurity awareness training to all employees. (Answer: 2\n- Multi-factor authentication (High), 3 - Cybersecurity Awareness\nTraining (Medium), 1 – Penetration Test (Low) - due to the significant\neffort and potential cost.)\n\n\\textbf{Q15:} You are advising a small business owner on cybersecurity\nrisk management. Describe two specific recommendations you would make,\nexplaining the rationale behind each recommendation. (Answer: Example:\nImplement a strong password policy and conduct regular backups of all\ncritical data – to protect against unauthorized access and data loss,\nrespectively.)\n\n\\subsubsection{Part C: Synthesis \\& Evaluation (2 Critical Thinking\nChallenges)}\\label{part-c-synthesis-evaluation-2-critical-thinking-challenges}\n\n\\textbf{Q16:} A company is considering migrating its entire IT\ninfrastructure to the cloud. Identify five significant cybersecurity\nrisks associated with this migration, and propose a mitigation strategy\nfor each risk. (Answer: Expect a lengthy response outlining risks like\ndata breaches, misconfiguration, vendor lock-in, compliance issues, and\ninsider threats – with corresponding mitigation recommendations, such as\nstrong access controls, regular security audits, and robust contracts\nwith cloud providers.)\n\n\\textbf{Q17:} Describe a scenario where prioritizing a low-impact risk\nmight actually be the \\emph{most} strategic approach from a business\nperspective. Justify your reasoning. (Answer: Example: A minor\nvulnerability in a rarely accessed web server that presents a minimal\nthreat of disruption, but would be extremely costly and disruptive to\nfix. Accepting the risk and focusing resources on more critical\nvulnerabilities might be a more efficient use of resources, prioritizing\noverall business operations.)\n\n\\end{document}\n",
